The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Alchemist has decided to merge Delhi-based Valiant Healthcare with itself to consolidate its leadership in pharmaceutical and healthcare segment. The boards of both the companies have approved the merger proposal. The share swap ratio is, however, yet to be finalised. Valiant has 41 branded products and a turnover of Rs 20 crore. Alchemist reported a sales revenue of Rs 250 crore and a net profit of Rs 14.6 crore for the year ended June 30, 2005.

 India Cement?s wholly owned subsidiary, ICL Securities, has entered into a share sale and purchase agreement with Trishul Investments Pvt Ltd. The agreement entails the purchase of Visaka Cement Industry?s four lakh equity shares of Rs 10 each by ICL Securities at a price of Rs 10.25 a share, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. 

 Welspun Gujarat Stahl Rohren will raise $100 million through foreign currency convertible bonds (fccbs) or some other instruments.

 y has approved the issue of FCCBs or equity shares or convertible debentures for up to $100 million, the textile manufacturer has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange.

 Asian Tea amp; Exports will split its equity shares in 1:10 ratio. The company?s board has approved the split of shares of Rs 10 each into shares of Re 1 each, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. It has also approved the issue of 20 lakh convertible warrants, out of which five lakh warrants would be issued to promoters and 15 lakh to non-promoters at a price of Rs 26 per warrant. The company plans to increase its the authorised capital to Rs 20 crore.

 Larsen amp; Toubro?s associate company in Oman has bagged Rs 165-crore contract from Petroleum Development Oman LLC. The contract is for construction of 293 km of 132 kv overhead transmission lines interconnecting various existing substations, construction of new transmission lines and additional substations at PDO?s existing oil fields in central Oman, L amp;T has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange.

 Valson Industries will issue 7.50 lakh warrants on a preferential basis to the promoters of the company. The board of directors has approved the issue of warrants of Rs 10 each at a price of Rs 51 per share, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. Its shareholders will ratify the issue at the EGM slated for October 26.

 Trend micro Inc has upgraded its four-year-old liaison office in India into a 100 per cent subsidiary. The company has recorded a 122 per cent turnover growth in 2004-05. The new entity, Trend Micro India Pvt Ltd, will double its headcount to 20 professionals by 2007, a company release said.

